"n.摩天大楼 【英】 n. 摩天大楼 (a very tall modern city building) 【考】 bone : body / girder : skyscraper(身体有骨骼支撑/摩 天大楼有钢梁支撑) n. 摩天大楼 【记】sky天空, scrape(n /v 刮; 擦), r: 擦到天空的楼－摩天大楼 【参】sky-rocket(v (物价等)猛涨) 【类】bone: body = girder: skyscraper骨骼支撑身体 = 钢梁支撑摩天大楼 【记】擦着天顶的 skyscraper (n.)  very tall urban building, 1888, in a Chicago context, from sky (n.) + agent noun of scrape (v.). Used earlier for ""ornament atop a building"" (1883), ""very tall man"" (1857), ""high-flying bird"" (1840), ""light sail at the top of a mast"" (1794), and the name of a racehorse (1789). Compare cognate French gratte-ciel, from gratter ""to scrape"" + ciel ""sky;"" German Wolkenkratzer, from Wolke ""cloud"" + Kratzer ""scraper."" cloud-cleaver, an imaginary sail jokingly assumed to be carried by Yankee ships. [W. Clark Russell, ""Sailors' Word Book,"" 1883]"
